Introduction

  • PCa has the highest incidence and mort of all Ca in Swe males.
  • Incidence in Swe is comparable with contries using PSA testing for a long time, Swe still has a comparably high mortality.
  • Prostate cancer is the most common cancer diagnosis and the most common cause of cancer death in Swedish males.*
  • Prostate cancer incidence rates in Sweden are similar to other countries with frequent prostate-specific antigen (PSA) testing, while Swedish prostate cancer mortality rates are high.1

* http://www-dep.iarc.fr/NORDCAN/english/StatsFact.asp?cancer=261&country=752, accessed 2016-04-20

Today’s unstructured screening with PSA is ineffective

  • Todays unstructured PSA testing is inefficient
    • There is to much testing of low risk men
    • …too many biopsies of benin and low grade cancers
    • and simultanously high risk men are not treated
Over testing
  • 38% of men with PSA < 1 have a new test within 2.5 years 2
Over diagnosis
  • 60% of all men biopsied are negative
  • 50% of all cancers diagnosed are Gleason 6 3
Under treatment
  • 30% of men aged 50–59 with PSA≥10 ng/ml do not have a biopsy within 2 years
  • 17% of men aged 50–69 diagnosed with advanced prostate cancer had PSA≥4 ng/ml six months or earlier with no action

Prostate cancer screening trials

  • Two large clinical trials
    • where the European -ERSPC- showed a decrease in 27% mortality reduction
    • in the American counterpart -PLCO- screening had no effect on mortality
    • It is believed that the lack of effect was due high PSA testing in the control arm
  • The European Randomised study of Screening for Prostate Cancer (ERSPC) found a prostate cancer mortality rate ratio of 0.73 (95% CI 0.61–0.88) after 13 years of follow-up.4
  • In contrast, the Prostate, Lung, Colorectal and Ovarian (PLCO) trial in the US indicated that organised PSA testing has little effect on prostate cancer mortality (due to control contamination).5

From randomised controlled trials (RCTs) to policy

  • RCTs are the gold standard for evidence on the effects of interventions
  • However they are expensive, slow to conduct, only address specific forms of intervention and may offer limited evidence on longer-term effects
  • How can we extrapolate from RCTs to other interventions and longer-term outcomes?
  • Either: Use the observed RCTs with expert judgement
  • Or: Simulate for interventions using a natural history model.

Natural history modelling

  • Natural history (NH) modelling describes the course from disease onset to recovery or death. The modelling is motivated by biological mechanisms.
  • Natural history modelling can be used to:
    • to generalise results from RCTs
    • predict effects for changing RCT protocols
    • calculate cost-effectiveness using predicted lifetime costs and quality of life

Screening and natural histories: stochastic life-lines (microsimulation)

  • only in a simulated data, not be observable.
  • Stochastic life lines generated by the microsimulation
  • man in a scenario without screening
  • man in a scenario with screening
  • classic timings in a screening context
  • how do we use this?

Research question: How should we plan for better prostate cancer testing?

Parameters affecting screening include:

  • Test characteristics for different tests (e.g. PSA, S3M, 4K and PHI)
  • Screening ages
  • Re-screening intervals
  • Screening history
  • Screening test compliance (if invitations are organised)
  • Biopsy compliance
  • Treatment effectiveness
  • etc…

Study 1

Background

  • computationally intensive to run the simulation with high precision
  • it is also computationally intensive to calibrate the model

Microsimulations are computationally intensive, particularly for model calibrations.

Aims

  • To provide an R package for microsimulation which is fast, light weight and more flexible to the R community.
  • To describe the design choices in our parallel discrete-event microsimulation R package.
  • To demonstrate its use in a small case study.

Technical details: R package

  • https://github.com/mclements/microsimulation
  • Fast and flexible discrete-event simulation (DES) microsimulation.
  • Common random number support.
  • In-simulation report reductions.
  • Support for distributed memory parallelism.

Libraries

In addition to its speed, C++ has several GPL-compatible libraries that has proven useful to us. The microsimulation package depends on:

RngStreams
a random number streams library.6
SSIM
a discrete event simulation library. The library defines the basic interface of a process, and provides the main simulation scheduler, including methods for creating, starting, and stopping processes.*
Boost libraries
including the tuple and unordered_map classes, and functions for hashing, binding and function pointers (all of which are provided by C++11/C++14). The Boost libraries were used so that the R library would be compliant with C++98, which was a requirement on the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) until.7
Rcpp
with extensions for wrapping vectors of tuples, and maps using tuples as keys.
* http://www.inf.usi.ch/carzaniga/ssim/

Case Study: FHCRC

  • Re-implement a prostate cancer model from the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center (FHCRC) model.89
  • Well validated prostate cancer NH model.
  • Open source prostate cancer screening model.

Model description

\begin{align} \log(y_{i}(t))&=\beta_{0i}+\beta_{1i}t +\beta_{2i}(t-t_{oi})I(t>t_{oi}) +\epsilon_i(t) \end{align}

where \(i\) is the subject index, \(t=\mathrm{age}-35\), \(y_{i}(t)\) is PSA at age \(t\), \(I(A)\) is a \(1\) if \(A\) is true and \(0\) otherwise, \(t_{oi}\) is the age of cancer onset and

  • \(\beta_{0i} \sim N(\mu_{0},\sigma_{0}^{2})\), which is a random intercept
  • \(\beta_{ki} \sim N(\mu_{k},\sigma_{k}^{2})I(\beta_{ki}>0),k=1,2\), which are random slopes
  • \(\epsilon_i(t) \sim N(0,\tau^{2})\), for measurement error.

Onset

The disease onset rate has the hazard:

\begin{align} \lambda_{o}(t) &= \gamma_{o}t \label{eq:onset} \end{align}

The cumulative probability of cancer onset \(R_{o}(t)=1-\exp\left(-\frac{\gamma_{o}}{2}t^{2}\right)\), where \(\hat{\gamma}_{0}=0.0005\). The onset probability density function is shown in Figure 6.

Density of cancer onset

Transition rates

The hazards of transitioning between states (i.e., healthy, preclinical, clinical, localized, metastatic) are dependent on \(t\) and \(\tilde{y}_i(t)=y_i(t)-\epsilon_i(t)\) (mean log-PSA for individual \(i\)).

Clinical diagnosis after metastasis for low, and high grade tumours is \(\propto PSA\), where \(\theta_{c1}\) is the post-metastasis clinical diagnosis hazard for low-grade cases and \(\theta_{c2}\) is the post-metastasis clinical diagnosis hazard for low-grade cases.

\begin{align} \lambda_{c}(t)&=\theta_{c1}\tilde{y}_{i}(t)\label{eq:cal}\\ \lambda_{c}(t)&=\theta_{c2}\theta_{c1}\tilde{y}_{i}(t)\label{eq:cah} \end{align}

The change in PSA values after cancer onset is assumed to differ by Gleason grade, with a common change for Gleason grades 6–7 and a common change for Gleason grade 8+.

Transition rates metastatic disease

The rate for metastatic disease for low and high grade tumors is \(\propto PSA\), where \(\gamma_{m}\) is the metastasis hazard for low-grade cases and \(\theta_{m}\) is the metastasis hazard for high-grade cases.

\begin{align} \lambda_{m}(t)&=\gamma_{m}\tilde{y}_{i}(t)\\ \lambda_{m}(t)&=\theta_{m}\gamma_{m}\tilde{y}_{i}(t) \end{align}

The clinical diagnosis rate before metastasis for low and high grade tumors is \(\propto PSA\), where \(\gamma_{c1}\) is the pre-metastasis clinical diagnosis hazard for low-grade cases and \(\gamma_{c2}\) is the hazard for pre-metastasis clinical diagnosis for high-grade cases.

\begin{align} \lambda_{c}(t)&=\gamma_{c1}\tilde{y}_{i}(t)\label{eq:cbl}\\ \lambda_{c}(t)&=\gamma_{c2}\gamma_{c1}\tilde{y}_{i}(t)\label{eq:cbh} \end{align}

Study 2

Would organised prostate cancer testing be cost-effective in Sweden?

Background

  • Current testing is opportunistic
  • Would organised testing be better
  • Social styrelsen has reopened its investigation on prostate cacner screening
  • Current testing is opportunistic.
  • Would organised testing be effective and lower costs?
  • Organising testing could be done in a multitude of ways.

Methods

  • Implement the FHCRC model using our package.810
  • Incorporate Swedish input data.
  • Calibrate (or fit) NH parameters using Swedish calibration targets.
  • Validate the model predictions using Swedish data.
  • Evaluate the cost-effectiveness of organised screening, with assumptions on cost and compliance.

Background: Cost-effectiveness

  • Cancer screening policies may be based on cost-effectiveness analysis (CEA), where the expected lifetime costs and health utilities for different policies are compared.
  • CEA can take a health sector or societal perspective.
  • The cost-effectiveness from the microsimulation can be described using utilities and costs for screening intervention \(k\), such that:
\begin{align*} \mathrm{Effectiveness}_k =& \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n \int_0^\infty \frac{dU_{ik}(t)}{(1+\delta)^t}\\ \mathrm{Costs}_k =& \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n \int_0^\infty \frac{dC_{ik}(t)}{(1+\delta)^t} \end{align*}

where we simulate for \(n\) individuals with index \(i\), with individual-based cumulative utilities \(U_{ik}(t)\) and costs \(C_{ik}(t)\) at time \(t\), with discounting \(\delta\) (e.g. \(\delta=0.03\)).

Background: STHLM3 main findings

The STHLM3 study was published in Lancet Oncology 2015:

  • Given the same number of Gleason 7+ cancers as PSA 3+, S3M reduced Gleason 6 cancers by 17% and reduced benign biopsies by 44%.

Methods: extended modelled states

Methods: extending FHCRC to model S3M

  • We initially wanted a longitudinal model for S3M, however follow-up data are not yet available.
  • For parsimony, we assume that S3M is positive when: for Gleason 7+ cancers, PSA is above 3 ng/ml; and for Gleason 6 cancers and men without cancer, PSA is above a threshold based on the STHLM3 false positive fractions.

Study 4

  • Is a methods paper.
  • use approximate Baysian computations for calibrating the model for study 3.
  • Publish methods in study 4

Calibration of a prostate cancer natural history microsimulation model using approximate Bayesian computation.

Background & Aim

  • First two studies the natural history model was calibrated using the Nelder-Mead algorithm.13
  • The dynamic and stochastic nature of our model could however provide a multiplicity of local solutions, which would be better handled by a global search algorithm. Preparations to make the simulation scale was done in study 1.
  • We aim to apply Approximate Baysian Computation (ABC) for both calibration and sensitivity analysis for Study 3.

Methods

Approximate Bayesian Computation (ABC) uses data from the observed marginal distribution for estimation.14

We will
  • prepare objective prior distributions, with uniform distribution for unknown parameters and Gaussian distributions for point estimates from the literature;
  • calibrate the simulation to the observed data using ABC;
  • investigate the model sensitivity using the selected model predictions

Concern

A potential theoretical concern relates to identifiability: does the data provide any information on the parameters of interest? If not, then we will need to use parameters from the literature as plug-in estimates. Note that the Swedish data are more extensive than are available in most other countries, which we expect to improve the validity of the fitted models.

Study 5

Develop a browser-based tool for allowing health-care decision makers to investigate different prostate cancer screening scenarios

Background & Aim

  • There is a need to better inform health-care decision makers about the benefits and harms of different prostate cancer screening policies.
  • As not all public policy planners are R-users. We aim to develop a browser-based tool to ease the comparison of different approaches to prostate cancer screening.

Prototype

Conclusions

  • Microsimulation is useful to plan for cancer screening, particularly in the context of personalised screening, as indicated by its increased use in the field (e.g. CISNET, NICE, USPSTF).
  • We contribute with tools and prediction results for the use of these methods in the Swedish context.
  • These models are complex and care is required to ensure that they are valid.

Potential discussion items

  • Overall: How can we assess whether a model is sufficiently valid for each research question?
  • Can we use one-way sensitivity analysis for Study 2? Or do we need to use probabilistic sensitivity analysis, possibly using a sample from the posterior distribution?
  • Do we need to represent T3+ progression within the localised state? This is motivated by a crude loco-regional/metastatic split in the FHCRC model.
  • How should we model for S3M?
  • From the review, the NICE appraisal found that PHI and PCA3 were not considered to be reliable and cost-effective. Does this appraisal have any implications for S3M?
